[30.53309, "o", "> "]
[30.533142, "o", "AFFECTED RULES:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.533416, "o", "- Rule 4: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.533463, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.533767, "o", "- Rule 5: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.533801, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.533832, "o", "> "]
[30.534003, "o", "- Rule 6: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.534037, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.53407, "o", "> "]
[30.534231, "o", "- Rule 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.534256, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.534287, "o", "> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.534322, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.534364, "o", "ROOT CAUSE:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.534393, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.534421, "o", "> "]
[30.535109, "o", "The iptables ruleset implements a flawed User-Agent filtering mechanism that blocks HTTP/HTTPS traffic not containing the string \"Mozilla\" in the packet payload. The rules process in order:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.535153, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.535182, "o", "> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.535209, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.535563, "o", "1. Rules 4-5 only ACCEPT traffic to ports 80/443 if the string \"Mozilla\" is found in the packet\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.535589, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.535622, "o", "> "]
[30.535808, "o", "2. Rules 6-7 DROP all remaining traffic to ports 80/443\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.535841, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.535871, "o", "> "]
[30.536176, "o", "3. This creates an effective whitelist that only allows browsers with \"Mozilla\" in their User-Agent\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.536209, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.536242, "o", "\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.536334, "o", "WHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP DOESN'T:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.536366, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.536612, "o", "- SSH (port 22): Rule 3 provides unconditional ACCEPT for all TCP traffic to port 22\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.536648, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.536958, "o", "- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Conditional ACCEPT requiring \"Mozilla\" string match, followed by explicit DROP\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.536992, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.537023, "o", "> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.537073, "o", "WHY CURL HANGS:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.5371, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.537409, "o", "Curl's default User-Agent is \"curl/[version]\" which doesn't contain \"Mozilla\". When curl sends HTTP requests:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.537442, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.537652, "o", "1. The initial TCP SYN packet has no payload, so no \"Mozilla\" string is present\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.537694, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.537841, "o", "2. The packet doesn't match rule 4/5 (no \"Mozilla\" found)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.537873, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.538025, "o", "3. The packet matches rule 6/7 and gets DROPped\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.538061, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.538195, "o", "4. Curl never receives a response and hangs waiting\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.538224, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.538255, "o", "\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.538286, "o", "> "]
[30.538826, "o", "Note: nmap shows ports as \"open\" because it likely only performs SYN scans or uses probes that happen to match the string filter, or because ESTABLISHED,RELATED rule (rule 2) allows response packets through.\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.538868, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> \r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.538903, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.538953, "o", "RECOMMENDATION:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.538983, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.539187, "o", "The string matching approach is fundamentally flawed for several reasons:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.539227, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.539446, "o", "1. It breaks legitimate tools like curl, wget, API clients, and monitoring systems\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.539474, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.539661, "o", "2. String matching on packet payloads is computationally expensive\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.539688, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.539877, "o", "3. It can be easily bypassed by adding \"Mozilla\" to any User-Agent\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.539918, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.540132, "o", "4. It may not work reliably due to packet fragmentation or encrypted traffic\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.54016, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.54019, "o", "\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.540218, "o", "> "]
[30.540434, "o", "The organization should remove the string matching requirement (rules 4-5) and either:\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.540464, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.540645, "o", "- Allow all HTTP/HTTPS traffic unconditionally (like SSH), OR\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.540679, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.540926, "o", "- Implement proper application-layer filtering using a web application firewall (WAF)\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.54096, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.541154, "o", "- Use connection rate limiting instead if DDoS protection is the goal\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.541185, "o", "\u001b[?2004h> "]
[30.541218, "o", "EOF\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.544044, "o", "\u001b[?2004h"]
[30.544081, "o", "user@d43547fce9fc:~/pentest$ "]
[30.630901, "i", "cat finding.txt\n"]
[30.631019, "o", "cat finding.txt\r\n\u001b[?2004l\r"]
[30.63196, "o", "FINDING: HTTP/HTTPS Traffic Blocked by String Matching Rules\r\n\r\nAFFECTED RULES:\r\n- Rule 4: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Rule 5: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -m string --string \"Mozilla\" --algo bm -j ACCEPT\r\n- Rule 6: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j DROP\r\n- Rule 7: -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 443 -j DROP\r\n\r\nROOT CAUSE:\r\nThe iptables ruleset implements a flawed User-Agent filtering mechanism that blocks HTTP/HTTPS traffic not containing the string \"Mozilla\" in the packet payload. The rules process in order:\r\n\r\n1. Rules 4-5 only ACCEPT traffic to ports 80/443 if the string \"Mozilla\" is found in the packet\r\n2. Rules 6-7 DROP all remaining traffic to ports 80/443\r\n3. This creates an effective whitelist that only allows browsers with \"Mozilla\" in their User-Agent\r\n\r\nWHY SSH WORKS BUT HTTP DOESN'T:\r\n- SSH (port 22): Rule 3 provides unconditional ACCEPT for all TCP traffic to port 22\r\n- HTTP/HTTPS (ports 80/443): Conditional ACCEPT requiring \"Mozilla\" string match, followed "]
[30.632045, "o", "by explicit DROP\r\n\r\nWHY CURL HANGS:\r\nCurl's default User-Agent is \"curl/[version]\" which doesn't contain \"Mozilla\". When curl sends HTTP requests:\r\n1. The initial TCP SYN packet has no payload, so no \"Mozilla\" string is present\r\n2. The packet doesn't match rule 4/5 (no \"Mozilla\" found)\r\n3. The packet matches rule 6/7 and gets DROPped\r\n4. Curl never receives a response and hangs waiting\r\n\r\nNote: nmap shows ports as \"open\" because it likely only performs SYN scans or uses probes that happen to match the string filter, or because ESTABLISHED,RELATED rule (rule 2) allows response packets through.\r\n\r\nRECOMMENDATION:\r\nThe string matching approach is fundamentally flawed for several reasons:\r\n1. It breaks legitimate tools like curl, wget, API clients, and monitoring systems\r\n2. String matching on packet payloads is computationally expensive\r\n3. It can be easily bypassed by adding \"Mozilla\" to any User-Agent\r\n4. It may not work reliably due to packet fragmentation or encrypted traffic\r\n\r\nThe organization should remov"]
[30.632094, "o", "e the string matching requirement (rules 4-5) and either:\r\n- Allow all HTTP/HTTPS traffic unconditionally (like SSH), OR\r\n- Implement proper application-layer filtering using a web application firewall (WAF)\r\n- Use connection rate limiting instead if DDoS protection is the goal\r\n"]
[30.632136, "o", "\u001b[?2004huser@d43547fce9fc:~/pentest$ "]
